You're not getting away.

73
00:06:46,780 --> 00:06:48,140
I won't let--

74
00:06:48,140 --> 00:06:48,380
[GUNSHOT]

75
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:49,120
[SCREAMING]

76
00:06:50,200 --> 00:06:50,900
[GUNSHOTS]

77
00:06:51,080 --> 00:06:52,200
[GROANING]

78
00:06:53,720 --> 00:06:54,420
[PANTING]

79
00:06:56,920 --> 00:06:58,320
[COUGHING]

80
00:07:01,240 --> 00:07:02,640
[SCREAMING]

81
00:07:03,380 --> 00:07:04,260
[PANTING]

82
00:07:04,260 --> 00:07:05,680
(crowd murmuring)

83
00:07:10,900 --> 00:07:11,720
- Stop pushing!

84
00:07:15,580 --> 00:07:16,940
- This side is no good!

85
00:07:20,180 --> 00:07:22,620
Please, help us!

86
00:07:23,420 --> 00:07:24,120
- Someone help us!

87
00:07:24,460 --> 00:07:25,720
Let us out of here!

88
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:27,560
- Listen, do not panic.

89
00:07:28,040 --> 00:07:30,180
Everyone, please remain calm, I beg of you.

90
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:33,520
Follow the directions of the security guard so that we can--

91
00:07:34,260 --> 00:07:37,420
Sir! All the doors have been locked from the outside!

92
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,040
That can't be!

93
00:07:40,340 --> 00:07:43,380
Whatever happens, you will take Mr. Schuwald with you, understood?

94
00:07:43,600 --> 00:07:44,080
Yes, sir!

95
00:07:44,680 --> 00:07:46,600
So, have they found an escape route?

96
00:07:47,560 --> 00:07:47,860
Huh?

97
00:07:48,340 --> 00:07:52,600
Can you tell me just where you plan on taking Mr. Schuwald in this sea of fire?

98
00:07:54,860 --> 00:07:56,920
Come on! We must break down the door!

99
00:07:57,340 --> 00:07:57,760
Right!

100
00:08:04,300 --> 00:08:11,960
The books are burning. So many of them alight. The flames quickly consuming everything they touch.

101
00:08:12,340 --> 00:08:18,480
You describe all of this with such damp calmness. The flames. The chaos.

102
00:08:19,560 --> 00:08:24,260
You're getting quite a thrill out of sharing this hellish scene with me, aren't you?

103
00:08:25,300 --> 00:08:30,300
It's how you always sounded when you read to me, and now you're going to take my place.

104
00:08:31,200 --> 00:08:33,440
No, I've since given up on that.

105
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:38,440
Something that's even more compelling has popped into my head.

106
00:08:46,120 --> 00:08:49,460
You're not afraid, even now, Mr. Shuvalt.

107
00:08:50,600 --> 00:08:51,620
Answer me this.

108
00:08:52,340 --> 00:08:53,800
Where did you come from?

109
00:08:55,120 --> 00:08:56,220
Who are you?

110
00:08:56,760 --> 00:08:57,720
Or what?

111
00:09:07,720 --> 00:09:09,200
Can you see me now?

112
00:09:10,240 --> 00:09:16,940
I know you can barely see anything, but when I'm this close to you...

113
00:09:19,140 --> 00:09:20,600
What can you see?

114
00:09:22,260 --> 00:09:25,140
What do you see when you look into my eyes?

115
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:33,440
I was born in a town that was straight out of a fairy tale.

116
00:09:35,380 --> 00:09:42,620
Many people died there, and when I walked away, I held hands with my other self.

117
00:09:47,340 --> 00:09:52,180
To me, it seemed like we were the only two people in the world.

118
00:09:55,160 --> 00:09:58,280
Neither one of us possessed a real name.

119
00:09:58,280 --> 00:09:59,000
(eerie music)

120
00:10:10,780 --> 00:10:13,580
(heavy breathing)

121
00:10:18,580 --> 00:10:19,860
(heavy breathing)

122
00:10:26,900 --> 00:10:27,620
(gunshots)

123
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:40,560
- Hey, lady!

124
00:10:47,020 --> 00:10:48,380
Wait, it's you.

125
00:10:48,580 --> 00:10:52,820
Dieter, do you know this young lady? Have you seen her somewhere before?

126
00:10:59,860 --> 00:11:00,800
It's burning!

127
00:11:23,140 --> 00:11:29,220
I forgot some papers. I need you to go retrieve them for me. Go to the mansion and get them.

128
00:11:29,220 --> 00:11:31,360
They're on the desk in the study.

129
00:11:39,080 --> 00:11:40,120
These, huh?

130
00:11:43,480 --> 00:11:44,220
Oh.

131
00:11:56,160 --> 00:11:57,440
It's my mom.

132
00:12:08,660 --> 00:12:15,960
"Herflig Detective Services, investigative report about Margot Langer and her death."

133
00:12:16,220 --> 00:12:22,540
Margot Langer, whose real name was Helenka Novakova, was born in Prague, Czechoslovakia

134
00:12:22,540 --> 00:12:24,300
on August 12, 1955.

135
00:12:24,300 --> 00:12:28,660
In the spring of 1970, when she was 15 years old,

136
00:12:28,760 --> 00:12:30,620
she somehow illegally gained entrance

137
00:12:30,620 --> 00:12:32,000
into former West Germany.

138
00:12:35,260 --> 00:12:37,420
Four years after entering Germany,

139
00:12:37,660 --> 00:12:40,120
Margot became a high-class call girl in Munich

140
00:12:40,120 --> 00:12:43,040
with a clientele consisting mainly of politicians

141
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:44,600
and influential businessmen.

142
00:12:45,060 --> 00:12:47,260
Even though her name was secret in high society,

143
00:12:47,480 --> 00:12:48,440
she became famous.

144
00:12:48,860 --> 00:12:52,100
Our client in this investigation, Hans-Georg Schuwald,

145
00:12:52,100 --> 00:12:54,660
was one of her more generous and steady patrons.

146
00:12:55,900 --> 00:12:58,280
Oh, Father, even after it all,

147
00:12:58,360 --> 00:13:00,800
you were still trying to find out more about Mother.

148
00:13:02,680 --> 00:13:06,040
At age 22, she bore Mr. Schuwald a son.

149
00:13:08,120 --> 00:13:11,780
That male child was given the name of Carl.

150
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:15,660
Carl, are you listening to me?

151
00:13:16,080 --> 00:13:16,940
This is important.

152
00:13:17,360 --> 00:13:19,880
Take this money and ride the train on track number 5.

153
00:13:20,660 --> 00:13:21,980
What about you, Mom?

154
00:13:22,540 --> 00:13:24,960
Honey, I already told you, I can't go with you.

155
00:13:25,760 --> 00:13:27,400
I don't want to go alone, Mom!

156
00:13:27,520 --> 00:13:28,580
You have no choice!

157
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:31,220
If you stay with me, they'll cart you off to some orphanage!

158
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:33,660
Around here, people will mock you as the son of a whore!

159
00:13:35,980 --> 00:13:37,200
Now go on!

160
00:13:37,580 --> 00:13:38,740
What about my dad?

161
00:13:40,180 --> 00:13:42,560
Why doesn't he help us? Doesn't he love me?

162
00:13:42,700 --> 00:13:44,060
Why'd he abandon us?

163
00:13:47,900 --> 00:13:55,900
Don't hate him if he turns you away, because Mommy doesn't hate him even now.

164
00:13:58,820 --> 00:13:59,760
I'll miss you.

165
00:14:02,060 --> 00:14:02,600
Mom!

166
00:14:06,240 --> 00:14:06,900
Mom!

167
00:14:10,920 --> 00:14:15,040
Her son Carl was moved around to many different sets of foster parents

168
00:14:15,060 --> 00:14:19,720
The young man went through a lot, but eventually ended up in a loving family.

169
00:14:20,620 --> 00:14:24,840
But he felt as if he was always... always alone in the world.

170
00:14:26,220 --> 00:14:28,500
Of course it wouldn't say that in the report.

171
00:14:30,580 --> 00:14:35,620
Margot Langer remained a top high-class prostitute, but retired in 1992.

172
00:14:36,660 --> 00:14:43,600
Furthermore, there are rumors that Langer was involved in an affair with the president of an underground bank just before her retirement.

173
00:14:49,680 --> 00:14:55,020
Investigating Margot's alleged affair, a lot of information was learned about this underground bank's operation.

174
00:14:55,920 --> 00:15:00,700
This bank laundered money for Germany's black market companies for five years starting in 1991.

175
00:15:01,660 --> 00:15:08,180
"Money laundering" is the term used for an organization in the business of taking illegal funds and turning them into legal currency.

176
00:15:11,440 --> 00:15:17,920
After her retirement from prostitution, Margot Langer left Munich and lived in Offenbach-Hesse.

177
00:15:18,940 --> 00:15:22,060
This is a picture of the apartment building that she lived in at that time.

178
00:15:22,780 --> 00:15:26,180
She shared her third floor apartment with a young man about age 18.

179
00:15:26,820 --> 00:15:28,940
The nature of their relationship is unknown.

180
00:15:30,300 --> 00:15:33,360
Margot Langer lived in Offenbach for nearly four years,

181
00:15:33,360 --> 00:15:38,060
until on November 2nd, 1996, she was found dead on Haida Street.

182
00:15:38,600 --> 00:15:42,520
According to police files, her death was the work of a phantom killer.

183
00:15:43,200 --> 00:15:44,560
The culprit was never found.

184
00:15:45,580 --> 00:15:46,240
Oh, Mother.

185
00:15:48,100 --> 00:15:48,640
Damn.

186
00:15:49,660 --> 00:15:54,100
Margot Langer sent a letter to a close friend three months before her untimely death.

187
00:15:54,600 --> 00:15:57,840
We were able to obtain the letter and have attached a copy to this report.

188
00:16:05,040 --> 00:16:08,160
Oh my god, this is her handwriting.

189
00:16:13,240 --> 00:16:18,520
I have finally retired from working and living a very peaceful life.

190
00:16:20,220 --> 00:16:24,200
In this piece, I'm filled with thoughts of my lost son.

191
00:16:25,400 --> 00:16:27,740
I also think about my best friend from Prague.

192
00:16:28,460 --> 00:16:31,240
We tried to escape from Czechoslovakia together.

193
00:16:31,240 --> 00:16:35,600
but she was captured at the border and taken back to Prague.

194
00:16:37,040 --> 00:16:41,300
Later, I heard she gave birth to twins and was very happy.

195
00:16:43,100 --> 00:16:46,900
Recently, I met a young man who is about the same age as my son.

196
00:16:48,480 --> 00:16:51,420
He looks exactly like my friend in Prague.

197
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:57,860
When I'm with him, I feel like I'm talking to my own son.

198
00:16:59,780 --> 00:17:04,140
I'm sure my boy has become a fine young man, just like him.

199
00:17:05,900 --> 00:17:08,440
He must have grown up to live a happy life.

200
00:17:09,660 --> 00:17:11,080
That's what I hope for.

201
00:17:14,160 --> 00:17:15,680
I'm all right now, Mom.

202
00:17:15,820 --> 00:17:18,740
And I know that I'll never feel alone again.

203
00:17:21,680 --> 00:17:25,100
I know Dad sent me here because he wanted me to read this.

204
00:17:25,740 --> 00:17:26,760
Now I get it.

205
00:17:27,860 --> 00:17:29,060
I understand what she meant.

206
00:17:30,080 --> 00:17:31,620
I understand completely.

207
00:17:33,720 --> 00:17:34,760
It's all right.

208
00:17:35,680 --> 00:17:36,620
I understand.

209
00:17:43,020 --> 00:17:44,060
Damn it.

210
00:17:44,360 --> 00:17:46,580
Every one of these doors has been locked tight.

211
00:17:47,120 --> 00:17:49,740
Dieter, did you find a phone to call the fire department yet?

212
00:17:50,180 --> 00:17:50,940
Yes, sir.

213
00:17:50,980 --> 00:17:51,580
I called them.

214
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:53,840
How could this have happened?

215
00:17:54,120 --> 00:17:55,700
What the hell's going on in there?

216
00:17:58,860 --> 00:17:59,840
(thunder rumbling)

217
00:18:06,380 --> 00:18:09,320
- Break the door, break the door!

218
00:18:09,820 --> 00:18:10,680
(coughing)

219
00:18:18,980 --> 00:18:20,300
(panting)

220
00:18:23,800 --> 00:18:24,520
- Out of the way.

221
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:26,680
Everyone move!

222
00:18:34,580 --> 00:18:35,280
(gunshots)

223
00:18:48,980 --> 00:18:51,060
Help him! Help him!

224
00:18:51,200 --> 00:18:51,980
Try to...

225
00:18:54,580 --> 00:18:56,220
Come on, you guys!

226
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:00,240
Harder! Harder!

227
00:19:14,260 --> 00:19:17,580
Now stay calm! Don't push! Go one at a time!

228
00:19:18,980 --> 00:19:19,880
Nobody panic!

229
00:19:20,700 --> 00:19:23,340
Help evacuate the women and elderly first!

230
00:19:23,940 --> 00:19:25,180
Thank you so much!

231
00:19:25,540 --> 00:19:27,900
Without your help, none of us here would have had a chance!

232
00:19:29,600 --> 00:19:31,000
Two shots left.

233
00:19:32,020 --> 00:19:33,720
Huh? Hey, where are you going?

234
00:19:34,600 --> 00:19:36,860
Are you crazy?!

235
00:19:57,180 --> 00:19:59,980
(dramatic music)

236
00:20:24,640 --> 00:20:26,040
Johan...

237
00:20:55,140 --> 00:20:57,180
[eerie music]

238
00:21:06,020 --> 00:21:07,160
[eerie music]

239
00:21:10,020 --> 00:21:10,060
♪ ♪

240
00:21:10,140 --> 00:21:10,360
- [panting]

241
00:21:12,060 --> 00:21:13,180
[eerie music]

242
00:21:13,460 --> 00:21:14,420
♪ ♪

243
00:21:14,980 --> 00:21:16,040
[screaming]

244
00:21:17,460 --> 00:21:18,500
- No, don't!

245
00:21:20,200 --> 00:21:22,360
- Tenma, please, you can't shoot Johan!

246
00:21:23,160 --> 00:21:23,440
- Nina.

247
00:21:25,880 --> 00:21:27,240
Hold on, what are you doing?

248
00:21:27,780 --> 00:21:28,700
Nina, don't!

249
00:21:30,020 --> 00:21:31,440
Don't do it!

250
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:41,480
(yells)

251
00:21:51,440 --> 00:21:53,120
(dramatic music)

252
00:22:00,540 --> 00:22:01,420
(gun firing)

253
00:22:05,900 --> 00:22:07,240
- Nina, don't shoot!

254
00:22:07,840 --> 00:22:08,920
Don't do it, Nina!

255
00:22:09,480 --> 00:22:10,340
(gun firing)

256
00:22:12,800 --> 00:22:14,440
(gun firing)

257
00:22:20,260 --> 00:22:21,660
Lina!

258
00:23:04,620 --> 00:23:05,800
(ethereal music)

259
00:23:38,960 --> 00:23:40,360
[MUSIC]

